POKEMON CARD IDENTIFICATION

Identifies a Pokemon card from a photo. Instead of trying to classify which
set a card is from, it turns the card image into a numeric "fingerprint"
and finds the closest match out of everything we've indexed - basically
how real card-scanning apps do it.


CORE PIPELINE

Three scripts build the system, run in this order:

Scripts/build_reference.py - Stage 1, matches our card images to the Pokemon TCG API, downloads the official images + metadata, writes reference_manifest.csv

Scripts/train_embedding.py - Stage 2, trains the embedding model (ResNet-50 + contrastive learning) that turns a card image into a 256-number fingerprint

Scripts/build_index.py - Stage 3, runs every card through the trained model and builds the searchable fingerprint index

Each one feeds into the next, so run them in order. Stage 1 and 3 need
Card_Dataset/ (our card images - not in this repo, see Setup below).


SETUP

pip install tensorflow requests numpy

Pokemon TCG API key goes in Scripts/key.txt (just the key, one line) or set
POKEMONTCG_API_KEY as an environment variable. Not tracked in git.

Card_Dataset/ (our card images from Kaggle)

PROJECT STRUCTURE

Scripts/build_reference.py - Stage 1
Scripts/train_embedding.py - Stage 2
Scripts/build_index.py - Stage 3
Scripts/identifycard_pseudocode.txt - Stage 4 logic spec

Reference/reference_manifest.csv - Stage 1 output, matched cards + metadata
Reference/match_report.txt - Stage 1 output, pairing results summary
Reference/api_sets.json - Stage 1 output, raw set catalog from the API
Reference/card_index_embeddings.npy - Stage 3 output, fingerprint for every card
Reference/card_index_metadata.csv - Stage 3 output, identity info, same order as the embeddings

Models/encoder_best.keras - Stage 2 output, the trained model

aug_diagnostic/ - proof the augmentation is actually creating different
views per card, not just re-encoding the same image, see
_ALL_CARDS_overview.png


CURRENT STATUS

Stage 1 (data pairing): done, 20,088 of 20,863 cards matched to the API (99%)

Stage 2 (training): done, 98.4% accuracy picking the correct card out of
the full catalog, tested against simulated phone-photo distortion (glare,
blur, lighting)

Stage 3 (index): done, all 20,863 cards fingerprinted and searchable,
including the ~4% that didn't have confirmed API data

Stage 4 (identify + backend): not built yet. Scripts/identifycard_pseudocode.txt
is the logic spec for whoever builds the actual backend - how to
fingerprint a photo, compare it to the index, and return a match.

Haven't tested on real phone photos yet - the 98.4% is against simulated
distortion of clean images, not actual photos. That's next.